{% submission %}

{% submission-part type="problem" %}

Helping students learn to write without the distraction of the internet and the temptation of AI. Writing on paper in class is not a sustainable solution and many kids have computer accommodations. I know lockdown browsers exist but the ones I’ve seen 1) cost too much, 2) don’t allow formatting, and 3) are full lockdown so students can’t access any other sites at all, which precludes a recursive and engaged writing process that allows for research while drafting. We don’t have a way of allowing students to type in class without at the same time having access to the entire internet including LLMs, and this is a constant, shifting obstacle to our ability to teach them how to write. 

{% /submission-part %}

{% submission-part type="proposed-solution" %}

I mean… a lockdown browser, or something like that, where students can write a full essay and also access certain sites that we pre-allow, maybe? They’d have to sign in to it. And it would need to also record typing history so we could see any copy-pastes. Something like that??

{% /submission-part %}

{% /submission %}